llm_answer:
Based on the provided context, the role of the Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission (IEBC) in electoral disputes is outlined in Article 88(4)(e). According to this article, the IEBC is responsible for:

(e) the settlement of electoral disputes, including disputes relating to or arising from nominations but excluding election petitions and disputes subsequent to the declaration of election results;

This means the IEBC has the mandate to resolve electoral disputes that occur during the nomination process, but not those that arise after the results have been declared. Election petitions, which are disputes brought after the results have been declared, are handled by the courts, not the IEBC.

