Based on the provided context, the grounds for disqualification from running for Parliament in Kenya are outlined in Article 99(2) of the Constitution. These grounds include:

(a) being a State officer or other public officer, other than a member of Parliament;
(b) having held office as a member of the Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission within the five years preceding the election;
(c) not being a citizen of Kenya for at least ten years immediately preceding the date of election;
(d) being a member of a county assembly;
(e) being of unsound mind;
(f) being an undischarged bankrupt;
(g) being subject to a sentence of imprisonment of at least six months at the time of registration as a candidate or election; and
(h) having misused or abused a State office or public office, or contravened Chapter Six of the Constitution.

Additionally, a person is disqualified if they are removed from office under the Constitution or legislation, as per Article 103(1)(c). This could include removal on grounds such as gross violation of the Constitution, abuse of office, or incapacity, as outlined in Article 181 for county governors, which may be applicable by analogy to members of Parliament.

