llm_answer:
Based on the provided context, the eligibility criteria for members of the Public Service Commission are outlined in Article 233(3). A person is not eligible for appointment as a member of the Commission if they:

(a) have held office, or stood for election as a member of Parliament or of a county assembly, or been a member of the governing body of a political party, within the preceding five years;

(b) holds any State office;

(c) is, or has been, a candidate for election as a member of Parliament or of a county assembly; or

(d) is, or has been, the holder of an office in any political organisation that sponsors or supports a candidate for election as a member of Parliament or of a county assembly.

However, clauses (c) and (d) cease to apply to a person after two general elections for Parliament have been held since the person ceased to be such a candidate or office holder.

The grounds for removing the Inspector-General from office are:

(a) serious violation of the Constitution or any other law, including a contravention of Chapter Six;
(b) gross misconduct, whether in the performance of the office holder’s functions or otherwise;
(c) physical or mental incapacity to perform the functions of office;
(d) incompetence;
(e) bankruptcy; or
(f) any other just cause.

These grounds are outlined in Article 245(7) of the Kenya 2010 Constitution.

